Date:8/9/2010 3:19:34 PM
From:E_K_S
Hi Bordeauxman -

Welcome to the Value Investing thread. I see that you are a recent member to SI
and hope the different ideas here help you pick future winners.

I only pay attention to institutional holders if they are known for their value
approach to investing. It reaffirms my pick.

One of my more recent buys was supported by a very large "Buy" from a Sovereign
Wealth Fund. The company was Noble Group L (OTC:NOBGF). Although the company
had doubled in value from when I first discovered it, I started a position
because I liked the assets they owned. I was lucky to have established my
position prior to the announcement that a China sovereign wealth fund became a
minoity owner in NOBGF.

Here is a site that provides a List of Sovereign Wealth Funds and their recent
activity.

http://www.swfinstitute.org/tag/noble-group/

From the article:"...According to the NY Times, “A company here that is partly
owned by the Chinese government has quietly purchased a 5.1 percent stake in
the only American-owned provider of enriched uranium for use in civilian
nuclear reactors. The company that bought the stake, the Noble Group, is the
world’s second-largest commodities trading and logistics company after Cargill
and is based here. One of its minority owners is the Chinese government’s
sovereign wealth fund...."

====================================================================

Therefore, institutional ownership is just more information you can use in your
due diligence. I generally do not put too much weight in the information but I
like it when I am in at a lower price when one of these institutions starts
their position.

I do pay attention to large successful individual equity buyers such as Buffet
or Icahn. Sometimes I will follow them in on their large "buys". MOT is one
example but it has not paid off yet.

EKS
