From:Jurgis Bekepuris
Personally, I don't look at who the Top Institutional Holders or in general
holders (e.g. here on SI) are. I've tried to play this game and mostly it was a
fool's game for me. Even when one saw Buffett buying or selling positions,
following him did not really work for me.

Sure I respect Buffett's positions and arguments about them, I also respect
investments and choices of some other professional investors and a number of
people here on SI. I look at almost every stock someone mentions but ultimately
it's my decision whether I invest or not. Some people have a better fit to my
investing style so I might look at their choices more or sooner, but that's it.

Somebody else buying or selling or holding might have a very tiny influence,
but mostly not. As you saw from other replies, other people here on SI and some
professional investors look at the holder data much more than I do.

Some names create opportunities for buying or selling. Cramer's followers
sometimes pile into a stock which leads to good sell point. Or they sell-off
something which leads to good buy. Still the decision for me is based on a
price and a company and not on what other people do. :)
