From:E_K_S
Hi Paul -

Re: GMXR and other E&P companies w/ proven reserves (ie Hard Assets)

Here is my thinking, The 10 year bond market rate is pointing to deflation and
a general concern of a contracting economy. My strategy is to acquire "real"
assets that have an instinct long term value and use my high priced dollars to
buy them.

That's why, I am not too concerned to speculate with a few of the E&P companies
as long as they do not have too much debt and have sufficient current cash flow
to pay their bills. Proven reserves "in the ground" are good too.

Proven reserves are good if they can be bought at a discount. The land assets
are good as long as they own it out right and have not liened it to the banks
to run their current operations.

Picked up a speculative starter position of GMXR based on this thinking. Their
balance sheet shows sufficient cash to maintain their operations. LT debt is
about $5.00/share but not too high based on their proven reserves. Stock
selling at 0.60 BV.

As of December 31, 2009, it had proved reserves of 355.3 billion cubic feet of
natural gas equivalent; and 252 net producing wells in east Texas.

